[src:gamma-beta-functions/beta-function] The beta function is useful in computing and representing the scattering amplitude for Regge trajectories.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/beta-function] Furthermore, it was the first known scattering amplitude in string theory, first conjectured by Gabriele Veneziano.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/beta-function] It also occurs in the theory of the preferential attachment process, a type of stochastic urn process.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/beta-function] The beta function is also important in statistics, e.g. for the beta distribution and beta prime distribution.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/beta-function] As briefly alluded to previously, the beta function is closely tied with the gamma function and plays an important role in calculus.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/beta-function] Even if unavailable directly, the complete and incomplete beta function values can be calculated using functions commonly included in spreadsheet or computer algebra systems.
