[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] In mathematics, the **gamma function** (represented by ⁠ $\Gamma$ ⁠, capital Greek letter gamma) is the most common extension of the factorial function to complex numbers.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] First studied by Daniel Bernoulli, the gamma function $\Gamma (z)$ is defined for all complex numbers z except non-positive integers, and $\Gamma (n)=(n-1)!$ for every positive integer ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] Since the gamma function has no zeros, its reciprocal ${\frac {1}{\Gamma }}$ is an entire function.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] Other extensions of the factorial function do exist, but the gamma function is the most popular and useful.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] It appears as a factor in various probability-distribution functions and other formulas in the fields of probability, statistics, analytic number theory, and combinatorics.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] The gamma function can be seen as a solution to the interpolation problem of finding a smooth curve $y=f(x)$ that connects the points of the factorial sequence: $(x,y)=(n,n!)$ for all positive integer values of ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] The simple formula for the factorial, $x!=1\cdot 2\cdot 3\cdots x$ is only valid when x is a positive integer, and no elementary function has this property, but a good solution is the gamma function ⁠ $f(x)=\Gamma (x+1)$ ⁠.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] The gamma function is not only smooth but analytic (except at the non-positive integers), and it can be defined in several explicit ways.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] However, it is not the only analytic function that extends the factorial, as one may add any analytic function that is zero on the positive integers, such as $k\sin(m\pi x)$ for an integer ⁠ m ⁠.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] Such a function is known as a pseudogamma function, the most famous being the Hadamard function.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] But this still does not give a unique solution, since it allows for multiplication by any periodic function $g(x)$ with $g(x)=g(x+1)$ and ⁠ $g(0)=1$ ⁠, such as ⁠ $g(x)=e^{k\sin(m\pi x)}$ ⁠.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] One way to resolve the ambiguity is the Bohr–Mollerup theorem, which shows that $f(x)=\Gamma (x)$ is the unique interpolating function for the factorial, defined over the positive reals, which is logarithmically convex, meaning that $y=\log f(x)$ is convex.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] The notation $\Gamma (z)$ is due to Legendre.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] If the real part of the complex number z is strictly positive (⁠ $\Re (z)>0$ ⁠), then the integral $\Gamma (z)=\int _{0}^{\infty }t^{z-1}e^{-t}\,dt$ converges absolutely, and is known as the **Euler integral of the second kind**.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] Thus we have shown that $\Gamma (n)=(n-1)!$ for any positive integer n by induction.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] The identity ${\textstyle z\Gamma (z)=\Gamma (z+1)}$ can be used (or, yielding the same result, analytic continuation can be used) to uniquely extend the integral formulation for $\Gamma (z)$ to a meromorphic function defined for all complex numbers ⁠ z ⁠, except integers less than or equal to zero.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] It is this extended version that is commonly referred to as the gamma function.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] If m is not an integer then this equation is meaningless since, in this section, the factorial of a non-integer has not been defined yet.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] In fact, the above assumption produces a unique definition of $\Gamma (z)$ as ⁠ $(z-1)!$ ⁠.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] The infinite product for the reciprocal ${\frac {1}{\Gamma (z)}}=z\prod _{n=1}^{\infty }\left[\left(1+{\frac {z}{n}}\right)/{\left(1+{\frac {1}{n}}\right)^{z}}\right]$ is an entire function, converging for every complex number ⁠ z ⁠.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] The definition for the gamma function due to Weierstrass is also valid for all complex numbers z except non-positive integers: $\Gamma (z)={\frac {e^{-\gamma z}}{z}}\prod _{n=1}^{\infty }\left(1+{\frac {z}{n}}\right)^{-1}e^{z/n},$ where $\gamma \approx 0.577216$ is the Euler–Mascheroni constant.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] This is the Hadamard product of $\textstyle {\frac {1}{\Gamma (z)}}$ in a rewritten form.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] The duplication formula is a special case of the multiplication theorem (see Eq.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] See Particular values of the gamma function for calculated values.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] However, these numbers $\Gamma (r)$ are not known to be expressible by themselves in terms of elementary functions.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] In general, when computing values of the gamma function, we must settle for numerical approximations.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] When restricted to the positive real numbers, the gamma function is a strictly logarithmically convex function.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] The last of these statements is, essentially by definition, the same as the statement that ⁠ $\psi ^{(1)}(x)>0$ ⁠, where $\psi ^{(1)}$ is the polygamma function of order 1.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] To prove the logarithmic convexity of the gamma function, it therefore suffices to observe that $\psi ^{(1)}$ has a series representation which, for positive real x, consists of only positive terms.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] There are also bounds on ratios of gamma functions.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] This growth is faster than exponential, ⁠ $\exp(\beta x)$ ⁠, for any fixed value of ⁠ $\beta$ ⁠.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] The behavior for non-positive z is more intricate.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] Euler's integral does not converge for ⁠ $\Re (z)\leq 0$ ⁠, but the function it defines in the positive complex half-plane has a unique analytic continuation to the negative half-plane.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] One way to find that analytic continuation is to use Euler's integral for positive arguments and extend the domain to negative numbers by repeated application of the recurrence formula, $\Gamma (z)={\frac {\Gamma (z+n+1)}{z(z+1)\cdots (z+n)}},$ choosing n such that $z+n$ is positive.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] The product in the denominator is zero when z equals any of the integers ⁠ $0,-1,-2,\ldots$ ⁠.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] Thus, the gamma function must be undefined at those points to avoid division by zero; it is a meromorphic function with simple poles at the non-positive integers.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] There is in fact no complex number z for which ⁠ $\Gamma (z)=0$ ⁠, and hence the reciprocal gamma function ${\textstyle {\dfrac {1}{\Gamma (z)}}}$ is an entire function, with zeros at ⁠ $z=0,-1,-2,\ldots$ ⁠.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] The gamma function rises to either side of this minimum.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] The gamma function must alternate sign between its poles at the non-positive integers because the product in the forward recurrence contains an odd number of negative factors if the number of poles between z and $z+n$ is odd, and an even number if the number of poles is even.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] There are many formulas, besides the Euler integral of the second kind, that express the gamma function as an integral.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] Let C be a Hankel contour, meaning a path that begins and ends at the point ∞ on the Riemann sphere, whose unit tangent vector converges to −1 at the start of the path and to 1 at the end, which has winding number 1 around 0, and which does not cross ⁠ $[0,\infty )$ ⁠.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] Fix a branch of $\log(-t)$ by taking a branch cut along $[0,\infty )$ and by taking $\log(-t)$ to be real when t is on the negative real axis.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] The reflection formula leads to the closely related expression ${\frac {1}{\Gamma (z)}}={\frac {i}{2\pi }}\int _{C}(-t)^{-z}e^{-t}\,dt,$ which is valid whenever ⁠ $z\not \in \mathbb {Z}$ ⁠.
