[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] Taking the limit for $a\to \infty$ gives the formula.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] An alternative notation introduced by Gauss is the $\Pi$ -function, a shifted version of the gamma function: $\Pi (z)=\Gamma (z+1)=z\Gamma (z)=\int _{0}^{\infty }e^{-t}t^{z}\,dt,$ so that $\Pi (n)=n!$ for every non-negative integer ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] The shifted reciprocal gamma function is sometimes denoted ⁠ $\pi (z)={\frac {1}{\Pi (z)}}$ ⁠, an entire function.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] The values presented here are truncated rather than rounded.) The complex-valued gamma function is undefined for non-positive integers, but in these cases the value can be defined in the Riemann sphere as ⁠ $\infty$ ⁠.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] Because the gamma and factorial functions grow so rapidly for moderately large arguments, many computing environments include a function that returns the natural logarithm of the gamma function, often given the name `lgamma` or `lngamma` in programming environments or `gammaln` in spreadsheets.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] This grows much more slowly, and for combinatorial calculations allows adding and subtracting logarithmic values instead of multiplying and dividing very large values.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] The digamma function, which is the derivative of this function, is also commonly seen.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] is often used since it allows one to determine function values in one strip of width 1 in z from the neighbouring strip.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] In particular, starting with a good approximation for a z with large real part one may go step by step down to the desired ⁠ z ⁠.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] The coefficients of the terms with $k>1$ of $z^{1-k}$ in the last expansion are simply ${\frac {B_{k}}{k(k-1)}},$ where the $B_{k}$ are the Bernoulli numbers.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] The Bohr–Mollerup theorem states that among all functions extending the factorial functions to the positive real numbers, only the gamma function is log-convex, that is, its natural logarithm is convex on the positive real axis.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] Another characterisation is given by the Wielandt theorem.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] In a certain sense, the log-gamma function is the more natural form; it makes some intrinsic attributes of the function clearer.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] A striking example is the Taylor series of logΓ around 1: $\operatorname {log\Gamma } (z+1)=-\gamma z+\sum _{k=2}^{\infty }{\frac {\zeta (k)}{k}}\,(-z)^{k}\qquad \forall \;|z|<1$ with ⁠ $\zeta (k)$ ⁠ denoting the Riemann zeta function at ⁠ k ⁠.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] There also exist special formulas for the logarithm of the gamma function for rational ⁠ z ⁠.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] When $z=1$ it follows that $\int _{0}^{1}\operatorname {log\Gamma } (x)\,dx={\frac {1}{2}}\log(2\pi ),$ and this is a consequence of Raabe's formula as well.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] Bailey and his co-authors gave an evaluation for $L_{n}:=\int _{0}^{1}\log ^{n}\Gamma (x)\,dx$ when $n=1,2$ in terms of the Tornheim–Witten zeta function and its derivatives.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] The gamma function can be computed to fixed precision for $\Re (z)\in [1,2]$ by applying integration by parts to Euler's integral.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] When ⁠ $\Re (z)\in [1,2]$ ⁠ and ⁠ $x\geq 1$ ⁠, the absolute value of the last integral is smaller than ⁠ $(x+1)e^{-x}$ ⁠.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] By choosing a large enough ⁠ x ⁠, this last expression can be made smaller than $2^{-N}$ for any desired value ⁠ N ⁠.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] Thus, the gamma function can be evaluated to N bits of precision with the above series.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] A fast algorithm for calculation of the Euler gamma function for any algebraic argument (including rational) was constructed by E.A.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] For arguments that are integer multiples of ⁠ ${\tfrac {1}{24}}$ ⁠, the gamma function can also be evaluated quickly using arithmetic–geometric mean iterations (see particular values of the gamma function).
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] Unlike many other functions, such as a normal distribution, no obvious fast, accurate implementation that is easy to implement for the gamma function $\Gamma (z)$ is easily found.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] Therefore, it is worth investigating potential solutions.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] For the case that speed is more important than accuracy, published tables for $\Gamma (z)$ are easily found in an Internet search, such as the Online Wiley Library.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] Such tables may be used with linear interpolation.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] Greater accuracy is obtainable with the use of cubic interpolation at the cost of more computational overhead.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] If interpolation tables are not desirable, then the Lanczos approximation mentioned above works well for 1 to 2 digits of accuracy for small, commonly used values of ⁠ z ⁠.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p01] If the Lanczos approximation is not sufficiently accurate, the Stirling's formula for the Gamma Function may be used.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] One author describes the gamma function as "Arguably, the most common special function, or the least 'special' of them.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] The other transcendental functions [...] are called 'special' because you could conceivably avoid some of them by staying away from many specialized mathematical topics.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] The gamma function finds application in such diverse areas as quantum physics, astrophysics and fluid dynamics.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] The gamma distribution, which is formulated in terms of the gamma function, is used in statistics to model a wide range of processes; for example, the time between occurrences of earthquakes.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] The primary reason for the gamma function's usefulness in such contexts is the prevalence of expressions of the type ⁠ $f(t)e^{-g(t)}$ ⁠, which describe processes that decay exponentially in time or space.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Integrals of such expressions can occasionally be solved in terms of the gamma function when no elementary solution exists.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] The fact that the integration is performed along the entire positive real line might signify that the gamma function describes the cumulation of a time-dependent process that continues indefinitely, or the value might be the total of a distribution in an infinite space.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] It is of course frequently useful to take limits of integration other than 0 and $\infty$ to describe the cumulation of a finite process, in which case the ordinary gamma function is no longer a solution; the solution is then called an incomplete gamma function.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] An important category of exponentially decaying functions is that of Gaussian functions $ae^{-{\frac {(x-b)^{2}}{c^{2}}}}$ and integrals thereof, such as the error function.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] There are many interrelations between these functions and the gamma function; notably, the factor ${\sqrt {\pi }}$ obtained by evaluating ${\textstyle \Gamma \left({\frac {1}{2}}\right)}$ is the "same" as that found in the normalizing factor of the error function and the normal distribution.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] The integrals discussed so far involve transcendental functions, but the gamma function also arises from integrals of purely algebraic functions.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] In particular, the arc lengths of ellipses and of the lemniscate, which are curves defined by algebraic equations, are given by elliptic integrals that in special cases can be evaluated in terms of the gamma function.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] The gamma function can also be used to calculate "volume" and "area" of n -dimensional hyperspheres.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] The gamma function's ability to generalize factorial products immediately leads to applications in many areas of mathematics; in combinatorics, and by extension in areas such as probability theory and the calculation of power series.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Many expressions involving products of successive integers can be written as some combination of factorials, the most important example perhaps being that of the binomial coefficient.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] The example of binomial coefficients motivates why the properties of the gamma function when extended to negative numbers are natural.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] A binomial coefficient gives the number of ways to choose k elements from a set of n elements; if ⁠ $k>n$ ⁠, there are of course no ways.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] If ⁠ $k>n$ ⁠, then $(n-k)!$ is the factorial of a negative integer and hence infinite if we use the gamma function definition of factorials—dividing by infinity gives the expected value of ⁠ 0 ⁠.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] We can replace the factorial by a gamma function to extend any such formula to the complex numbers.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Generally, this works for any product wherein each factor is a rational function of the index variable, by factoring the rational function into linear expressions.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] If we have a way to calculate the gamma function numerically, it is very simple to calculate numerical values of such products.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] The number of gamma functions in the right-hand side depends only on the degree of the polynomials, so it does not matter whether $b-a$ equals 5 or 105.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] By taking the appropriate limits, the equation can also be made to hold even when the left-hand product contains zeros or poles.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] By taking limits, certain rational products with infinitely many factors can be evaluated in terms of the gamma function as well.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Due to the Weierstrass factorization theorem, analytic functions can be written as infinite products, and these can sometimes be represented as finite products or quotients of the gamma function.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] We have already seen one striking example: the reflection formula essentially represents the sine function as the product of two gamma functions.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Starting from this formula, the exponential function as well as all the trigonometric and hyperbolic functions can be expressed in terms of the gamma function.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] More functions yet, including the hypergeometric function and special cases thereof, can be represented by means of complex contour integrals of products and quotients of the gamma function, called Mellin–Barnes integrals.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] An application of the gamma function is the study of the Riemann zeta function.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Among other things, this provides an explicit form for the analytic continuation of the zeta function to a meromorphic function in the complex plane and leads to an immediate proof that the zeta function has infinitely many so-called "trivial" zeros on the real line.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] The gamma function has caught the interest of some of the most prominent mathematicians of all time.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Its history, notably documented by Philip J.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Davis in an article that won him the 1963 Chauvenet Prize, reflects many of the major developments within mathematics since the 18th century.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] In the words of Davis, "each generation has found something of interest to say about the gamma function.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] The problem of extending the factorial to non-integer arguments was apparently first considered by Daniel Bernoulli and Christian Goldbach in the 1720s.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] In particular, in a letter from Bernoulli to Goldbach dated 6 October 1729 Bernoulli introduced the product representation $x!=\lim _{n\to \infty }\left(n+1+{\frac {x}{2}}\right)^{x-1}\prod _{k=1}^{n}{\frac {k+1}{k+x}},$ which is well defined for real values of x other than the negative integers.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] He wrote to Goldbach again on 8 January 1730, to announce his discovery of the integral representation $n!=\int _{0}^{1}(-\log s)^{n}\,ds,$ which is valid when the real part of the complex number ⁠ n ⁠ is strictly greater than $-1$ (i.e., ⁠ $\Re (n)>-1$ ⁠).
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] By the change of variables ⁠ $t=-\ln s$ ⁠, this becomes the familiar Euler integral.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Euler published his results in the paper "De progressionibus transcendentibus seu quarum termini generales algebraice dari nequeunt" ("On transcendental progressions, that is, those whose general terms cannot be given algebraically"), submitted to the St.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Euler further discovered some of the gamma function's important functional properties, including the reflection formula.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] James Stirling, a contemporary of Euler, also attempted to find a continuous expression for the factorial and came up with what is now known as Stirling's formula.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Although Stirling's formula gives a good estimate of ⁠ $n!$ ⁠, also for non-integers, it does not provide the exact value.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Extensions of his formula that correct the error were given by Stirling himself and by Jacques Philippe Marie Binet.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Carl Friedrich Gauss rewrote Euler's product as $\Gamma (z)=\lim _{m\to \infty }{\frac {m^{z}m!}{z(z+1)(z+2)\cdots (z+m)}}$ and used this formula to discover new properties of the gamma function.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Although Euler was a pioneer in the theory of complex variables, he does not appear to have considered the factorial of a complex number, as instead Gauss first did.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Gauss also proved the multiplication theorem of the gamma function and investigated the connection between the gamma function and elliptic integrals.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Karl Weierstrass further established the role of the gamma function in complex analysis, starting from yet another product representation, $\Gamma (z)={\frac {e^{-\gamma z}}{z}}\prod _{k=1}^{\infty }\left(1+{\frac {z}{k}}\right)^{-1}e^{\frac {z}{k}},$ where $\gamma$ is the Euler–Mascheroni constant.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Weierstrass originally wrote his product as one for ⁠ $\textstyle {\frac {1}{\Gamma }}$ ⁠, in which case it is taken over the function's zeros rather than its poles.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Inspired by this result, he proved what is known as the Weierstrass factorization theorem—that any entire function can be written as a product over its zeros in the complex plane; a generalization of the fundamental theorem of algebra.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] The name gamma function and the symbol $\Gamma$ were introduced by Adrien-Marie Legendre around 1811; Legendre also rewrote Euler's integral definition in its modern form.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Although the symbol is an upper-case Greek gamma, there is no accepted standard for whether the function name should be written "gamma function" or "Gamma function" (some authors simply write "⁠ $\Gamma$ ⁠-function").
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] The alternative "pi function" notation $\Pi (z)=z!$ due to Gauss is sometimes encountered in older literature, but Legendre's notation is dominant in modern works.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] It is justified to ask why we distinguish between the "ordinary factorial" and the gamma function by using distinct symbols, and particularly why the gamma function should be normalized to $\Gamma (n+1)=n!$ instead of simply using ⁠ $\Gamma (n)=n!$ ⁠.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Consider that the notation for exponents, ⁠ $x^{n}$ ⁠, has been generalized from integers to complex numbers $x^{z}$ without any change.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Legendre's motivation for the normalization is not known, and has been criticized as cumbersome by some (the 20th-century mathematician Cornelius Lanczos, for example, called it "void of any rationality" and would instead use ⁠ $z!$ ⁠).
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Legendre's normalization does simplify some formulae, but complicates others.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] From a modern point of view, the Legendre normalization of the gamma function is the integral of the additive character $e^{-x}$ against the multiplicative character $x^{z}$ with respect to the Haar measure ${\textstyle {\frac {dx}{x}}}$ on the Lie group ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{+}$ ⁠.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Thus this normalization makes it clearer that the gamma function is a continuous analogue of a Gauss sum.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] It is somewhat problematic that a large number of definitions have been given for the gamma function.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Although they describe the same function, it is not entirely straightforward to prove the equivalence.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Stirling never proved that his extended formula corresponds exactly to Euler's gamma function; a proof was first given by Charles Hermite in 1900.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Instead of finding a specialized proof for each formula, it would be desirable to have a general method of identifying the gamma function.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] One way to prove equivalence would be to find a differential equation that characterizes the gamma function.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Most special functions in applied mathematics arise as solutions to differential equations, whose solutions are unique.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] However, the gamma function does not appear to satisfy any simple differential equation.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Otto Hölder proved in 1887 that the gamma function at least does not satisfy any *algebraic* differential equation by showing that a solution to such an equation could not satisfy the gamma function's recurrence formula, making it a transcendentally transcendental function.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] This result is known as Hölder's theorem.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] A definite and generally applicable characterization of the gamma function was not given until 1922.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] The Bohr–Mollerup theorem is useful because it is relatively easy to prove logarithmic convexity for any of the different formulas used to define the gamma function.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Taking things further, instead of defining the gamma function by any particular formula, we can choose the conditions of the Bohr–Mollerup theorem as the definition, and then pick any formula we like that satisfies the conditions as a starting point for studying the gamma function.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] This approach was used by the Bourbaki group.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Borwein & Corless review three centuries of work on the gamma function.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Although the gamma function can be calculated virtually as easily as any mathematically simpler function with a modern computer—even with a programmable pocket calculator—this was of course not always the case.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Until the mid-20th century, mathematicians relied on hand-made tables; in the case of the gamma function, notably a table computed by Gauss in 1813 and one computed by Legendre in 1825.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Tables of complex values of the gamma function, as well as hand-drawn graphs, were given in *Tables of Functions With Formulas and Curves* by Jahnke and Emde, first published in Germany in 1909.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] There was in fact little practical need for anything but real values of the gamma function until the 1930s, when applications for the complex gamma function were discovered in theoretical physics.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] As electronic computers became available for the production of tables in the 1950s, several extensive tables for the complex gamma function were published to meet the demand, including a table accurate to 12 decimal places from the U.S.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Double-precision floating-point implementations of the gamma function and its logarithm are now available in most scientific computing software and special functions libraries, for example TK Solver, Matlab, GNU Octave, and the GNU Scientific Library.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] The gamma function was also added to the C standard library (math.h).
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] Arbitrary-precision implementations are available in most computer algebra systems, such as Mathematica and Maple.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] PARI/GP, MPFR and MPFUN contain free arbitrary-precision implementations.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/gamma-function-p02] In some software calculators, such the Windows Calculator and GNOME Calculator, the factorial function returns $\Gamma (x+1)$ when the input x is a non-integer value.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] In mathematics, the **upper** and **lower incomplete gamma functions** are types of special functions which arise as solutions to various mathematical problems such as certain integrals.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] Their respective names stem from their integral definitions, which are defined similarly to the gamma function but with different or "incomplete" integral limits.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] The gamma function is defined as an integral from zero to infinity.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] This contrasts with the lower incomplete gamma function, which is defined as an integral from zero to a variable upper limit.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] Similarly, the upper incomplete gamma function is defined as an integral from a variable lower limit to infinity.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] The upper incomplete gamma function is defined as: $\Gamma (s,x)=\int _{x}^{\infty }t^{s-1}\,e^{-t}\,dt,$ whereas the lower incomplete gamma function is defined as: $\gamma (s,x)=\int _{0}^{x}t^{s-1}\,e^{-t}\,dt.$ In both cases s is a complex parameter, such that the real part of s is positive.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] The lower incomplete gamma and the upper incomplete gamma function, as defined above for real positive s and x, can be developed into holomorphic functions, with respect both to x and s, defined for almost all combinations of complex x and s.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] Complex analysis shows how properties of the real incomplete gamma functions extend to their holomorphic counterparts.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] By a theorem of Weierstrass, the limiting function, sometimes denoted as $\gamma ^{*}$ , $\gamma ^{*}(s,z):=e^{-z}\sum _{k=0}^{\infty }{\frac {z^{k}}{\Gamma (s+k+1)}}$ is entire with respect to both z (for fixed s) and s (for fixed z), and, thus, holomorphic on **C** × **C** by Hartogs' theorem.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] Hence, the following *decomposition* $\gamma (s,z)=z^{s}\,\Gamma (s)\,\gamma ^{*}(s,z),$ extends the real lower incomplete gamma function as a holomorphic function, both jointly and separately in z and s.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] It follows from the properties of $z^{s}$ and the Γ-function, that the first two factors capture the singularities of $\gamma (s,z)$ (at *z* = 0 or s a non-positive integer), whereas the last factor contributes to its zeros.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] The complex logarithm log *z* = log |*z*| + *i* arg *z* is determined up to a multiple of 2*πi* only, which renders it multi-valued.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] Functions involving the complex logarithm typically inherit this property.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] Among these are the complex power, and, since *z**s* appears in its decomposition, the γ-function, too.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] The indeterminacy of multi-valued functions introduces complications, since it must be stated how to select a value.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] The following set of rules can be used to interpret formulas in this section correctly.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] Sectors in **C** having their vertex at *z* = 0 often prove to be appropriate domains for complex expressions.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] A sector D consists of all complex z fulfilling *z* ≠ 0 and *α* − *δ* < arg *z* < *α* + *δ* with some α and 0 < *δ* ≤ *π*.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] Often, α can be arbitrarily chosen and is not specified then.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] If δ is not given, it is assumed to be π, and the sector is in fact the whole plane **C**, with the exception of a half-line originating at *z* = 0 and pointing into the direction of −*α*, usually serving as a branch cut.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] Note: In many applications and texts, α is silently taken to be 0, which centers the sector around the positive real axis.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] In particular, a single-valued and holomorphic logarithm exists on any such sector D having its imaginary part bound to the range (*α* − *δ*, *α* + *δ*).
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] Based on such a restricted logarithm, *z**s* and the incomplete gamma functions in turn collapse to single-valued, holomorphic functions on D (or **C**×*D*), called branches of their multi-valued counterparts on D.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] Adding a multiple of 2*π* to α yields a different set of correlated branches on the same set D.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] However, in any given context here, α is assumed fixed and all branches involved are associated to it.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] If |*α*| < *δ*, the branches are called principal, because they equal their real analogues on the positive real axis.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] Note: In many applications and texts, formulas hold only for principal branches.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] The values of different branches of both the complex power function and the lower incomplete gamma function can be derived from each other by multiplication of $e^{2\pi iks}$ , for k a suitable integer.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] This seems to justify setting *γ*(*s*, 0) = 0 for real *s* > 0.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] However, matters are somewhat different in the complex realm.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] Only if (a) the real part of s is positive, and (b) values *u**v* are taken from just a finite set of branches, they are guaranteed to converge to zero as (*u*, *v*) → (0, *s*), and so does *γ*(*u*, *v*).
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] On a single branch of *γ*(*b*) is naturally fulfilled, so **there** *γ*(*s*, 0) = 0 for s with positive real part is a continuous limit.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] Also note that such a continuation is by no means an analytic one.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] All algebraic relations and differential equations observed by the real *γ*(*s*, *z*) hold for its holomorphic counterpart as well.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] This is a consequence of the identity theorem, stating that equations between holomorphic functions valid on a real interval, hold everywhere.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] In particular, the recurrence relation and *∂γ*(*s*, *z*)/*∂z* = *z**s*−1 *e*−*z* are preserved on corresponding branches.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] The last relation tells us, that, for fixed s, γ is a primitive or antiderivative of the holomorphic function *z**s*−1 *e*−*z*.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] Consequently, for any complex *u*, *v* ≠ 0, $\int _{u}^{v}t^{s-1}\,e^{-t}\,dt=\gamma (s,v)-\gamma (s,u)$ holds, as long as the path of integration is entirely contained in the domain of a branch of the integrand.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] Any path of integration containing 0 only at its beginning, otherwise restricted to the domain of a branch of the integrand, is valid here, for example, the straight line connecting 0 and z.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] Since the final integral becomes arbitrarily small if only a is large enough, *γ*(*s*, *x*) converges uniformly for *x* → ∞ on the strip 1 ≤ Re(s) ≤ 2 towards a holomorphic function, which must be Γ(s) because of the identity theorem.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] It follows $\Gamma (s)=\lim _{x\to \infty }\gamma (s,x)$ for all complex s not a non-positive integer, x real and *γ* principal.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] As shown above, the first difference can be made arbitrarily small, if |*u*| is sufficiently large.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] Again referring to the behavior of *x**n* *e*−*x* for large x, we see that the last expression approaches 0 as R increases towards ∞.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] In total we now have: $\Gamma (s)=\lim _{|z|\to \infty }\gamma (s,z),\quad \left|\arg z\right|<\pi /2-\epsilon ,$ if s is not a non-negative integer, 0 < *ε* < *π*/2 is arbitrarily small, but fixed, and *γ* denotes the principal branch on this domain.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] As for the **upper incomplete gamma function**, a holomorphic extension, with respect to z or s, is given by $\Gamma (s,z)=\Gamma (s)-\gamma (s,z)$ at points (*s*, *z*), where the right hand side exists.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] Since $\gamma$ is multi-valued, the same holds for $\Gamma$ , but a restriction to principal values only yields the single-valued principal branch of $\Gamma$ .
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] When s is a non-positive integer in the above equation, neither part of the difference is defined, and a limiting process, here developed for *s* → 0, fills in the missing values.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] Complex analysis guarantees holomorphicity, because $\Gamma (s,z)$ proves to be bounded in a neighbourhood of that limit for a fixed z.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] To determine the limit, the power series of $\gamma ^{*}$ at *z* = 0 is useful.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] Here, $\operatorname {Ei}$ is the exponential integral, $\operatorname {E} _{n}$ is the generalized exponential integral, $\operatorname {erf}$ is the error function, and $\operatorname {erfc}$ is the complementary error function, $\operatorname {erfc} (x)=1-\operatorname {erf} (x)$ .
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] This continued fraction converges for all complex z, provided only that s is not a negative integer.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] The incomplete gamma functions are available in various of the computer algebra systems.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] Even if unavailable directly, however, incomplete function values can be calculated using functions commonly included in spreadsheets (and computer algebra packages).
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] In Excel, for example, these can be calculated using the gamma function combined with the gamma distribution function.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] These follow from the definition of the gamma distribution's cumulative distribution function.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] In Python, the Scipy library provides implementations of incomplete gamma functions under `scipy.special`, however, it does not support negative values for the first argument.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] The function `gammainc` from the mpmath library supports all complex arguments.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] This formula can be derived by repeated integration by parts.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] $P(s,x)$ and $Q(s,x)$ are implemented as `gammainc` and `gammaincc` in scipy.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] Results for $|z|\geq 1$ can be obtained by analytic continuation.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] Some special cases of this function can be simplified.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] These derivatives and the function $T(m,s,x)$ provide exact solutions to a number of integrals by repeated differentiation of the integral definition of the upper incomplete gamma function.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/incomplete-gamma-function] When combined with a computer algebra system, the exploitation of special functions provides a powerful method for solving definite integrals, in particular those encountered by practical engineering applications (see Symbolic integration for more details).
[src:gamma-beta-functions/lanczos-approximation] In mathematics, the **Lanczos approximation** is a method for computing the gamma function numerically, published by Cornelius Lanczos in 1964.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/lanczos-approximation] It is a practical alternative to the more popular Stirling's approximation for calculating the gamma function with fixed precision.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/lanczos-approximation] Here g is a real constant that may be chosen arbitrarily subject to the restriction that Re(*z* + *g* + ⁠1/2⁠) > 0.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/lanczos-approximation] The coefficients p, which depend on g, are slightly more difficult to calculate (see below).
[src:gamma-beta-functions/lanczos-approximation] The series A is convergent, and may be truncated to obtain an approximation with the desired precision.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/lanczos-approximation] By choosing an appropriate g (typically a small integer), only some 5–10 terms of the series are needed to compute the gamma function with typical single or double floating-point precision.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/lanczos-approximation] Thus computing the gamma function becomes a matter of evaluating only a small number of elementary functions and multiplying by stored constants.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/lanczos-approximation] Godfrey (2001) describes how to obtain the coefficients and also the value of the truncated series A as a matrix product.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/lanczos-approximation] The following implementation in the Python programming language works for complex arguments and typically gives 13 correct decimal places.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/lanczos-approximation] Note that omitting the smallest coefficients (in pursuit of speed, for example) gives totally inaccurate results; the coefficients must be recomputed from scratch for an expansion with fewer terms.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/multivariate-gamma-function] In mathematics, the **multivariate gamma function** Γ*p* is a generalization of the gamma function.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/multivariate-gamma-function] It is useful in multivariate statistics, appearing in the probability density function of the Wishart and inverse Wishart distributions, and the matrix variate beta distribution.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/multivariate-gamma-function] where $|S|$ denotes the determinant of S .
[src:gamma-beta-functions/multivariate-gamma-function] In both definitions, a is a complex number whose real part satisfies $\Re (a)>(p-1)/2$ .
[src:gamma-beta-functions/multivariate-gamma-function] Note that $\Gamma _{1}(a)$ reduces to the ordinary gamma function.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/multivariate-gamma-function] Where G is the Barnes G-function, the indefinite product of the Gamma function.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/multivariate-gamma-function] The function is derived by Anderson from first principles who also cites earlier work by Wishart, Mahalanobis and others.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/multivariate-gamma-function] There also exists a version of the multivariate gamma function which instead of a single complex number takes a p -dimensional vector of complex numbers as its argument.
[src:gamma-beta-functions/multivariate-gamma-function] It generalizes the above defined multivariate gamma function insofar as the latter is obtained by a particular choice of multivariate argument of the former.
